Francois Beausoleil wrote:
&gt; // In my TestStaticSerialization TestCase
&gt; public void testValidClass() {
&gt;     TestCase case = TestStaticSerialization(ValidClass.class);
&gt; 
&gt;     // Should never fail in any of these methods
&gt;     case.setUp();
&gt;     case.testEquals();
&gt;     case.testHashCode();
&gt;     case.testSerialization();
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; public void testInvalidClass() {
&gt;     TestCase case = TestStaticSerialization(InvalidClass.class);
&gt;     case.setUp();                        // Should fail here !
&gt;     case.testEquals();
&gt;     case.testHashCode();
&gt;     case.testSerialization();
&gt; }

One possibility is:
	TestResult result = new TestResult();
	case.run(result);
	assertEquals(0orWhatever, result.errorCount());
	assertEquals(0orWhatever, result.failureCount());
That&#39;s the way the tests coming with JUnit are asserted most of the
time. Using a TestListener would be more work but might be necessary if
you want to test the exact timing of failure/error occurrence.

Johannes
